oint 1 — Before-condition analysis in eminent domain. This scenario establishes the before-condition locational profile required for just compensation. In eminent domain appraisal, both positive and negative locational influences must be identified. Omitting the Pelham Road corridor negative (A) would overstate the before-condition value and produce an advocacy document, not a credible appraisal.", "Teaching Point 2 — Retained by property owner does not mean positive-only. Even though this appraiser is retained by the property owner, accurate locational analysis requires identifying Factor A as Negative. Students who omit or reclassify negative factors because of the retaining party are making an advocacy error. USPAP requires impartiality regardless of who signs the engagement letter.", "Teaching Point 3 — Cul-de-sac distractor. Factor F is not present — this is a through-lot on a residential block. Near road project assignments, students sometimes assume cul-de-sac configurations exist when the profile describes a through-street. Every factor identification requires a specific basis in the location description."]}'::jsonb,
