utral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — Distinguish infrastructure from amenity. Factor G (natural water amenity) is a deliberate distractor. Students who check it because of the wastewater association are misidentifying industrial infrastructure as a water feature. This distinction is especially important in litigation where opposing counsel will challenge any analytical imprecision in the appraiser''s factor list.", "Teaching Point 2 — Neutral for school district requires specific support. Factor C is Neutral not by default but because the profile provides specific evidence: average-performing, no documented premium. In litigation, the appraiser must articulate why each classification was made. ''The school district is average'' without market evidence is a vulnerable position under cross-examination.", "Teaching Point 3 — Identify all positives even when retained by plaintiff. Factors B, D, and E are positive locational influences that must be identified accurately. Students who omit them are producing an advocacy document. In litigation, positive factors must be identified because opposing counsel will exploit any omission as evidence of bias or analytical incompleteness."]}'::jsonb,
